To run multiple asynchronous tasks where each step depends on the result of the previous one, you use Promise Chaining. [1, 2] 
There are two primary ways to do this:
## 1. Using .then() Chaining
Each .then() receives the result of the previous promise and returns a new promise for the next step. [3, 4] 

const firstTask = () => new Promise(resolve => resolve("User123"));
const secondTask = (userId) => new Promise(resolve => resolve(`Data for ${userId}`));

firstTask()
    .then(userId => {
        console.log(userId);
        return secondTask(userId); // Return the next promise
    })
    .then(data => {
        console.log(data); // "Data for User123"
    })
    .catch(error => console.error(error)); // Single catch for the whole chain

## 2. Using async/await (Recommended)
This is "syntactic sugar" that makes your asynchronous code look and behave like synchronous code, which is much easier to read. [5, 6] 

async function runSequence() {
    try {
        // Pauses here until firstTask resolves
        const userId = await firstTask(); 
        
        // Pauses here until secondTask resolves using result from first
        const data = await secondTask(userId); 
        
        console.log(data);
    } catch (error) {
        console.error("An error occurred:", error);
    }
}

runSequence();

## Why use this?

* Sequential Execution: Ensures tasks run one by one rather than all at once.
* Data Dependency: Allows you to pass data from one step directly into the next.
* Avoids Callback Hell: Prevents deeply nested code (the "pyramid of doom"). [1, 2, 4, 5, 7] 

Pro Tip: If your tasks do not depend on each other, use [Promise.all()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Promise/all) to run them in parallel for better performance. [8, 9] 
